s of the Assimilation of Eastern European Jews, 1890–1940 -- tTHIRTEEN. Strangers No Longer: Jews and Postwar American Political Culture -- tFOURTEEN. Changing Places, Changing Cultures: Divergent Jewish Political Cultures -- tEpilogue: On Living in Two Cultures -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTwo creative centers of Jewish life rose to prominence in the twentieth century, one in Israel and the other in the United States. Although Israeli and American Jews share kinship and history drawn from their Eastern European roots, they have developed divergent cultures from their common origins, often seeming more like distant cousins than close relatives. This book explores why this is so, examining how two communities that constitute eighty percent of the world’s Jewish population have created separate identities and cultures.Using examples from literature, art, history, and politics, leading Israeli and American scholars focus on the political, social, and memory cultures of their two communities, considering in particular the American Jewish challenge to diaspora consciousness and the Israeli struggle to forge a secular, national Jewish identity. At the same time, they seek to understand how a sense of mutual responsibility and fate animates American and Israeli Jews who reside in distant places, speak different languages, and live within different political and social worlds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aJewszIsraelxIdentity. 0aJewszUnited StatesxAttitudes toward Israel. 0aJewszUnited StatesxIdentity. 0aJewszUnited StatesxSocial life and customs. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aArad, Gulie Ne’eman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBand, Arnold J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo